  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the engineering grade levels in VMware?",
  "response": "In VMware, engineering grade levels typically follow a structured hierarchy, similar to many other technology companies. While the exact titles and levels may vary, the general progression is as follows:\n\n1. **Software Engineer I (E1)**\n   - Entry-level position, typically for new graduates or those with limited experience.\n   - Focus on learning and contributing to small tasks and projects.\n\n2. **Software Engineer II (E2)**\n   - Mid-level position, typically for engineers with a few years of experience.\n   - More responsibility and involvement in larger projects, often working more independently.\n\n3. **Senior Software Engineer (E3)**\n   - Senior-level position, typically for engineers with significant experience.\n   - Lead projects, mentor junior engineers, and make significant technical decisions.\n\n4. **Staff Software Engineer (E4)**\n   - Highly experienced engineers, often considered technical experts.\n   - May lead multiple projects or teams, influence technical direction, and contribute to strategic decisions.\n\n5. **Senior Staff Software Engineer (E5)**\n   - Very experienced engineers with deep expertise and broad impact.\n   - Often involved in high-level technical strategy and cross-team initiatives.\n\n6. **Principal Software Engineer (E6)**\n   - Top-tier individual contributors with exceptional technical skills and influence.\n   - Drive company-wide technical initiatives and often act as thought leaders.\n\n7. **Distinguished Engineer (E7)**\n   - Highly prestigious position, often reserved for engineers with profound impact and recognition.\n   - Influence the entire company's technical direction and often work on the most critical projects.\n\n8. **Fellow**\n   - The highest technical position within VMware, reserved for a select few.\n   - Recognized as industry leaders with significant contributions to the field and company.\n\nPlease note that these titles and levels can vary, and VMware may have specific nuances or additional levels not listed here. It's always best to refer to VMware's internal documentation or career pages for the most accurate and up-to-date information.",
